1
00:00:00,605 --> 00:00:25,464
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah

2
00:00:26,321 --> 00:00:30,647
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:32,869 --> 00:00:34,212
So make sure that you're comfortable.

4
00:00:34,832 --> 00:00:40,901
So always begin your meditation by creating at least that physical comfort.

5
00:00:44,104 --> 00:00:53,476
So begin by making sure your basic posture is comfortable and then lifting up that spine without any tension.

6
00:00:57,152 --> 00:00:59,715
And then just begin to physically relax around it.

7
00:01:00,835 --> 00:01:09,063
Pass your attention over your forehead, your jaw, your shoulders, and just feel that relaxation coming.

8
00:01:09,082 --> 00:01:13,727
If there's any spots that are tense, like the shoulders, give them a squeeze.

9
00:01:13,847 --> 00:01:17,090
Or if you feel a lot of tension in the face, give it a squeeze.

10
00:01:17,171 --> 00:01:18,951
Screw it up and let it go.

11
00:01:23,796 --> 00:01:26,838
Sometimes a deep breath, remember, just holding it for a little while.

12
00:01:30,245 --> 00:01:31,266
And just letting it go.

13
00:01:44,141 --> 00:01:50,207
Now as you scan your body, as you feel the whole of your body, you may just feel the calmness there.

14
00:01:53,951 --> 00:01:55,834
So that calmness is Pasadi.

15
00:01:55,853 --> 00:01:58,496
It's one of the qualities, one of the factors of enlightenment.

16
00:01:59,707 --> 00:02:02,832
it can become quite delicious, that sense of calm.

17
00:02:06,817 --> 00:02:20,778
So having established that at a basic physical level, we can now just bring the attention to the breath, becoming aware of the sensations of the breath.

18
00:02:20,838 --> 00:02:26,948
Now you can do it at the nostrils, but with this sort of exercise, you can contact the abdomen,

19
00:02:28,783 --> 00:02:33,491
just the rising and falling of the abdomen, just the sensations there.

20
00:02:35,914 --> 00:02:41,965
And just get in touch with them, feel them, experience them as if you were feeling cloth.

21
00:02:46,050 --> 00:02:53,862
And what you're bringing to that is just awareness, which is the leading factor of enlightenment.

22
00:03:06,500 --> 00:03:27,985
And as you begin to become aware of those sensations, those gentle feelings, calm, pasadi feelings, calm feelings, the rising and falling of the abdomen, use a little noting word just to keep the mind steady, rising, falling.

23
00:03:30,128 --> 00:03:35,055
And if there's a gap after that out breath, feel a touch point like your hands

24
00:03:41,566 --> 00:04:11,387
rising falling touching as you contact these sensations these feelings as it were go closer to it get the feeling of focusing in it's a gentle thing if you're knitting your brow and forcing it then that's

25
00:04:12,868 --> 00:04:14,192
That's putting any pressure.

26
00:04:14,652 --> 00:04:17,178
You're just looking and you're focusing.

27
00:04:17,199 --> 00:04:26,321
It's like you're looking at a countryside and the distance you see something and suddenly your eyes stop and focus in on that object.

28
00:04:26,341 --> 00:04:29,528
Get that feeling of focusing down into the breath.

29
00:04:54,009 --> 00:05:21,334
well that's the concentration and all the effort you need is just to keep that focus in and hold it there in the old cameras you had to turn the lens to focus it now it's done by electric motor so the effort, the gentle effort just focusing in on the object are two factors of enlightenment and as you focus in on the object other things

30
00:05:21,685 --> 00:05:26,951
begin to fade into the distance, as it were.

31
00:05:26,971 --> 00:05:30,475
You become less aware of sounds, other feelings in the body.

32
00:05:31,536 --> 00:05:46,052
All this is a sign that you're beginning to focus in, to concentrate on the object.

33
00:05:46,072 --> 00:05:48,435
You can see it's very much a relaxation.

34
00:05:49,732 --> 00:05:58,880
And just drawing your attention more and more particularly into the sensations and feelings caused by the breath.

35
00:06:30,315 --> 00:06:33,879
So now we have a general calmness and awareness.

36
00:06:33,920 --> 00:06:35,021
We know what's going on.

37
00:06:36,002 --> 00:06:39,346
We can see, feel, experience the breath.

38
00:06:40,387 --> 00:06:44,913
There's a general focusing down and an energy to support it.

39
00:06:46,536 --> 00:07:00,271
Now we bring in the factor of investigating the dharma, which means that we don't just focus on the feelings and sensations, but on the quality of impermanence, transience, change

40
00:07:00,504 --> 00:07:01,146
process.

41
00:07:03,028 --> 00:07:04,428
Become aware of that now.

42
00:07:06,430 --> 00:07:23,367
This is the quality of investigating the Dharma.

43
00:07:23,387 --> 00:07:26,951
Now this is supported by the quality of equanimity, which means

44
00:07:27,774 --> 00:07:33,062
that we're not coming from a fixed position, some expectation, some idea.

45
00:07:34,644 --> 00:07:46,920
We actually want to experience the arising and passing away, first of all, of the gross long breath, the beginning and the end of the in-breath, the beginning and the end of the out-breath.

46
00:07:48,942 --> 00:07:55,351
And we can say, yes, the in-breath begins and ends.

47
00:07:56,411 --> 00:08:00,237
The out-breath begins and ends.

48
00:08:02,822 --> 00:08:08,391
Very simple.

49
00:08:12,858 --> 00:08:23,314
And as we draw our attention to that, you might feel a sort of joy, a sort of delicate energy in the body, and that's the interest.

50
00:08:24,593 --> 00:08:31,122
Now we've raised that wanting to know, a childlike curiosity.

51
00:08:34,788 --> 00:08:37,753
Am I really seeing things as they really are?

52
00:08:37,793 --> 00:08:45,825
Or am I just seeing a concept in the mind, an image in the mind?

53
00:09:39,653 --> 00:09:43,638
So hopefully now you're actually moving towards pure vipassana.

54
00:09:46,541 --> 00:09:51,746
Awareness, focusing and effort to keep us there.

55
00:09:53,649 --> 00:10:00,256
Calmness of the body and the joy of interest.

56
00:10:00,277 --> 00:10:08,326
Equanimity, not coming from a fixed position, investigating the quality of impermanence.

57
00:10:24,777 --> 00:10:31,345
As you observe the breath, you might notice that there's an image in the mind of the abdomen rising and falling.

58
00:10:32,206 --> 00:10:38,212
There's even an idea that something is rising and falling.

59
00:10:38,232 --> 00:10:43,438
These are mental concepts, mental constructs.

60
00:10:43,458 --> 00:10:47,224
Focus in more deeply into just the sensations.

61
00:11:44,629 --> 00:11:47,015
That brings us to the end of our little exercise.

62
00:11:53,932 --> 00:11:55,736
You see you can talk yourself into that.

63
00:12:29,990 --> 00:12:51,159
So, just going through these qualities, remember that all of this rests upon a quality of trust, a quality of faith, saddha, which is a spiritual faculty.

64
00:12:53,524 --> 00:12:57,229
We wouldn't be here if we didn't have that initial confidence.

65
00:12:58,407 --> 00:13:06,033
So when that confidence goes, for instance, the usual loss of confidence is in oneself, and nobody else can do it but not me.

66
00:13:07,735 --> 00:13:17,745
When you get that wavering, that doubt in the mind about one's own capacity, that's when you have to remind yourself that these qualities are natural to all human beings.

67
00:13:19,967 --> 00:13:21,729
And just there within us.

68
00:13:22,289 --> 00:13:25,613
It's not as though they are special qualities.

69
00:13:26,081 --> 00:13:33,910
to somebody who's a Buddha or who's already spiritually advanced.

70
00:13:34,231 --> 00:13:39,937
Once a child's over the age of seven, you can only talk to them into this sort of state.

71
00:13:41,820 --> 00:13:43,763
It's easy, any time before puberty.

72
00:13:46,525 --> 00:13:49,149
After that it gets very complicated.

73
00:13:51,491 --> 00:13:55,937
So, these qualities are

74
00:13:56,322 --> 00:14:00,346
Just to be developed, just like any other mental quality that we have.

75
00:14:02,109 --> 00:14:04,711
So we're very good at developing the negative qualities.

76
00:14:05,653 --> 00:14:08,797
We've learned how to do that very well.

77
00:14:08,817 --> 00:14:10,700
So you feel, you start whinging.

78
00:14:11,080 --> 00:14:11,900
So you know how to do that.

79
00:14:12,282 --> 00:14:14,664
You whinge.

80
00:14:15,446 --> 00:14:20,211
You know that sound with the whinge.

81
00:14:22,214 --> 00:14:23,134
And you just develop it.

82
00:14:23,895 --> 00:14:25,418
And at the end you become a whinger.

83
00:14:26,697 --> 00:14:33,586
So if you look at all these qualities that we've developed which are negative, all the irritations, same with depression.

84
00:14:33,606 --> 00:14:38,212
You feel a bit depressed, so you say to yourself, I'm depressed.

85
00:14:38,232 --> 00:14:39,975
Then you go around saying, it's really depressing.

86
00:14:39,995 --> 00:14:40,897
Everything's depressing.

87
00:14:42,339 --> 00:14:49,188
And then you start saying, subtly underneath it all is, I am a depressive.

88
00:14:50,451 --> 00:14:51,371
May I be depressed?

89
00:14:53,106 --> 00:14:54,749
And then you want to spread that out, you know.

90
00:14:55,089 --> 00:14:58,251
May all beings be depressed.

91
00:14:58,312 --> 00:15:00,293
Then you feel you're in communion.

92
00:15:00,654 --> 00:15:02,135
You look for other depressives.

93
00:15:03,697 --> 00:15:06,200
I once went to a Depressives Anonymous.

94
00:15:08,302 --> 00:15:09,023
A bit sad, really.

95
00:15:09,623 --> 00:15:11,024
They're all sat around in this circle.

96
00:15:11,905 --> 00:15:16,230
And the leader said, like everybody who'd like to, you know, just speak out.

97
00:15:16,309 --> 00:15:18,812
You know, it's like one of these counselling sessions.

98
00:15:19,432 --> 00:15:20,193
How do you feel?

99
00:15:21,405 --> 00:15:24,889
So everybody told everybody else how depressed they were.

100
00:15:24,909 --> 00:15:27,873
Everybody said, yeah, really depressing.

101
00:15:28,693 --> 00:15:29,615
And I was getting depressed.

102
00:15:31,236 --> 00:15:33,438
And there was one fellow who said he'd had a fantastic week.

103
00:15:33,458 --> 00:15:35,500
And you could see he was on a high, he was manic.

104
00:15:35,520 --> 00:15:37,043
He was lifting himself up, you know.

105
00:15:38,043 --> 00:15:39,806
So everybody was looking at him, you know.

106
00:15:43,889 --> 00:15:50,096
And then there was this lovely, lovely moment where the leader of the group said, well, I've had a very good week.

107
00:15:51,004 --> 00:15:55,150
And I was doing very well, you know, and I was keeping high.

108
00:15:55,912 --> 00:15:58,014
And it's all the experience of talking yourself into this high.

109
00:15:58,034 --> 00:16:03,322
And then I tripped over a pavement.

110
00:16:03,341 --> 00:16:09,089
So I wrote to the council and I said, you know, I've just tripped over your pavement and I've hurt myself.

111
00:16:09,890 --> 00:16:11,152
And I asked for compensation.

112
00:16:12,254 --> 00:16:15,158
Well, they wrote back and said that there was no compensation for that.

113
00:16:15,759 --> 00:16:17,581
So I felt really angry about that.

114
00:16:17,600 --> 00:16:18,361
And now I'm depressed.

115
00:16:18,932 --> 00:16:21,736
It's amazing.

116
00:16:21,756 --> 00:16:25,361
And I was out there thinking, hmm.

117
00:16:25,383 --> 00:16:29,469
So at the end of it, I gave this talk on how we make ourselves depressed.

118
00:16:33,193 --> 00:16:35,677
It was funny.

119
00:16:35,697 --> 00:16:39,023
And, you know, I said, well, I teach over just in North London there.

120
00:16:39,864 --> 00:16:41,986
The Bihar, I think I was teaching at the Bihar at the time.

121
00:16:43,687 --> 00:16:55,144
there's only a tube right, so about, of the 20 odd people that were in the room, maybe 7 or 8 came over to see me, and they all determined that they'd come over and learn this meditation so they wouldn't get so depressed.

122
00:16:56,947 --> 00:17:02,956
Well, they never turned up, I just presumed they got so depressed they couldn't come and see me.

123
00:17:02,975 --> 00:17:07,823
And it was, you know, I left that meeting feeling very sad, because

124
00:17:08,224 --> 00:17:10,267
They were obviously trying to help themselves.

125
00:17:10,287 --> 00:17:13,191
There was nothing immoral or wrong about it.

126
00:17:13,211 --> 00:17:14,573
It just hadn't clicked.

127
00:17:14,593 --> 00:17:23,242
They just hadn't understood how they were continuously recreating the same old scenes and just driving themselves deeper and deeper into depression.

128
00:17:25,665 --> 00:17:31,913
Anyway, they must, after a while, I heard anyway that they must have gotten really depressed because the money ran out and they had to stop the meetings.

129
00:17:33,454 --> 00:17:34,497
It's very unfortunate.

130
00:17:35,298 --> 00:17:37,319
Very depressing.

131
00:17:37,942 --> 00:17:45,111
So here you can see that through practices like metta, you can develop quite the opposite.

132
00:17:45,131 --> 00:17:57,265
Now, if you develop metta, that's loving-kindness, compassion, all those sorts of things, but you don't develop the vipassana, then you're laying over the top of your mind like a manic.

133
00:17:57,285 --> 00:18:01,289
You're laying over it this sort of icing, like an icing on top of dung.

134
00:18:03,251 --> 00:18:06,236
And when it cracks, you see, all this stuff comes pouring out.

135
00:18:06,256 --> 00:18:07,257
It's very depressing.

136
00:18:08,536 --> 00:18:17,190
So here, in the vipassana, we're actually trying to create a level of consciousness.

137
00:18:17,250 --> 00:18:19,272
Don't confuse that with a mental state.

138
00:18:20,955 --> 00:18:24,501
So I'm using mental state to mean a general state.

139
00:18:24,561 --> 00:18:32,535
So the physical feelings, for instance, that go with, say, we're talking about depression, the physical feelings that go with depression,

140
00:18:32,936 --> 00:18:38,502
The heart state, the depression in the heart, and the thoughts that go with that depression.

141
00:18:38,923 --> 00:18:41,385
All that I'm calling a mental state.

142
00:18:41,486 --> 00:18:45,190
This is, in the Pali, for those of you who know, that's citta.

143
00:18:45,210 --> 00:18:46,230
That's the mental state.

144
00:18:47,873 --> 00:18:56,623
Now, to associate with that, to identify with that, to go around saying I am depressed, is a level of consciousness.

145
00:18:56,762 --> 00:18:59,586
Because there, you believe yourself to be that state.

146
00:19:01,237 --> 00:19:03,659
So there's no separation between me and that.

147
00:19:04,319 --> 00:19:05,340
I am depressed.

148
00:19:05,361 --> 00:19:06,362
It's there in the sentence.

149
00:19:06,961 --> 00:19:11,046
The I and the depression are one and the same thing.

150
00:19:11,066 --> 00:19:16,070
Now what we're doing in our meditation is we have the same feelings as anybody who's depressed.

151
00:19:16,090 --> 00:19:21,496
You've got the sensations, you've got the heart feelings, and you've got the mental thinking that goes with it.

152
00:19:22,257 --> 00:19:23,877
But now you're observing it.

153
00:19:24,699 --> 00:19:27,281
You become an observer of your own inner state.

154
00:19:27,902 --> 00:19:29,943
So you must have pulled yourself out.

155
00:19:30,666 --> 00:20:00,336
out of that you no longer identifying with you no longer saying I am depressed you're saying there's depression that's it can you see that's a very different way of relating to ourselves it's a different level of consciousness and the image I gave you this morning of a cone on top of the cone looking down on this vicious circle so now what we discover is that we can develop beautiful mental states

156
00:20:00,721 --> 00:20:04,484
We do that with, you know, pleasurable things like ice cream and stuff.

157
00:20:04,826 --> 00:20:11,213
But here, when we develop these states, they're dependent within something within ourselves.

158
00:20:11,733 --> 00:20:13,936
So they're not dependent on something outside.

159
00:20:14,978 --> 00:20:16,058
The weather can be awful.

160
00:20:16,660 --> 00:20:17,981
There can be no ice cream.

161
00:20:18,102 --> 00:20:18,962
There can be no tea.

162
00:20:19,824 --> 00:20:25,611
And yet you can develop these beautiful mental states just by this inner exercise.

163
00:20:27,272 --> 00:20:27,413
Yeah?

164
00:20:27,953 --> 00:20:30,036
And you can see, all you have to do is just keep

165
00:20:30,471 --> 00:20:33,315
Just keep gently, gently pushing yourself.

166
00:20:33,335 --> 00:20:34,076
Just gently.

167
00:20:34,396 --> 00:20:36,439
When I say push, you see, it's against the grain.

168
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:45,910
The grain wants you to fall asleep, get tired, go to bed, take a walk, jump up and down, beans on toast.

169
00:20:45,930 --> 00:20:49,654
So when you go against that, it feels like you don't want to do it, you see.

170
00:20:49,674 --> 00:20:57,423
But as you keep doing it and these beautiful feelings start arising, the calmness, sense of joy, the wanting to know,

171
00:20:58,383 --> 00:21:00,525
then all your energy begins to move that way.

172
00:21:02,906 --> 00:21:07,270
And then very slowly these factors of enlightenment are becoming developed.

173
00:21:07,290 --> 00:21:10,453
And the Buddha says they have to be developed to perfection.

174
00:21:10,614 --> 00:21:14,738
The perfection is when you start having insights.

175
00:21:14,758 --> 00:21:26,127
So when it comes to all the negative stuff, these five hindrances that we've mentioned, the greed, the hatred, all that sort of stuff, you have to see how they arise

176
00:21:27,458 --> 00:21:31,082
and how they pass away, and how they are not maintained.

177
00:21:31,843 --> 00:21:33,184
You've got to see that process.

178
00:21:34,666 --> 00:21:39,913
That's the vipassana, when you're doing insight on these negative states that are arising.

179
00:21:40,594 --> 00:21:48,403
On the other side, you've got to see, now this is a spiritual faculty, this is a factor of enlightenment, this has to be developed.

180
00:21:49,924 --> 00:21:56,232
So the acuteness of my awareness, the sense of one-pointedness in the mind that we call concentration,

181
00:21:56,720 --> 00:22:04,509
That word concentration is unfortunate for us because it goes back to school and people giving us cuffs on the back of the head and told to concentrate.

182
00:22:05,852 --> 00:22:13,401
But actually, when you're interested in something, when you're really interested in something, have you ever had any problems with concentration?

183
00:22:15,544 --> 00:22:20,069
So it's raising that interest, that wanting to know, and immediately you get that focus.

184
00:22:20,590 --> 00:22:23,934
Immediately you get the mind coming into ekagata.

185
00:22:24,035 --> 00:22:25,737
Ekagata means going one way.

186
00:22:26,038 --> 00:22:26,337
It's not

187
00:22:26,673 --> 00:22:27,534
coming here and there.

188
00:22:29,497 --> 00:22:35,125
One-pointed is probably a much better word for us than concentration.

189
00:22:35,145 --> 00:22:37,048
A one-pointed attention.

190
00:22:37,288 --> 00:22:38,711
A one-pointed attention.

191
00:22:41,094 --> 00:22:46,643
So it all begins with this factor of sati, this awareness, which is essentially the Buddha mind.

192
00:22:46,663 --> 00:22:50,127
It's essentially that Buddha nature within us.

193
00:22:50,989 --> 00:22:51,849
Sati.

194
00:22:51,869 --> 00:22:52,431
It knows.

195
00:22:52,892 --> 00:22:54,053
There is this knowing.

196
00:22:55,075 --> 00:22:56,477
Its quality is knowing.

197
00:22:59,443 --> 00:23:04,853
In English we have this facility of making a verb into a noun.

198
00:23:05,453 --> 00:23:07,999
So there is the knowing.

199
00:23:08,058 --> 00:23:10,682
If you say consciousness, it blocks it into an object.

200
00:23:12,006 --> 00:23:17,174
Whereas if you think of knowing or the awakening, it gives you the sense of process.

201
00:23:17,234 --> 00:23:21,000
It gives you a sense of, it's not something, it's a faculty, it's an ability.

202
00:23:21,923 --> 00:23:22,042
Right?

203
00:23:22,646 --> 00:23:25,972
There's this knowing, sati, awareness.

204
00:23:26,232 --> 00:23:27,555
They've got all these other words for it.

205
00:23:27,615 --> 00:23:32,683
Mindfulness, being in the moment, being now, being here, all that sort of stuff.

206
00:23:32,703 --> 00:23:34,346
But its quality is it knows.

207
00:23:37,511 --> 00:23:46,426
So, as you place your awareness on the breath, so you always begin with that to create these faculties.

208
00:23:47,015 --> 00:23:52,420
So as you put your awareness on the breath, there is that raising of interest.

209
00:23:52,440 --> 00:23:54,823
I mean, I've done it slightly different, but you can do it another way.

210
00:23:54,863 --> 00:23:57,726
You can raise the interest by saying, oh, let's see this.

211
00:23:58,046 --> 00:23:58,906
Like, what is this?

212
00:23:59,126 --> 00:23:59,748
What is this?

213
00:24:00,327 --> 00:24:01,730
You can drop a question in there.

214
00:24:01,910 --> 00:24:02,530
What is this?

215
00:24:03,010 --> 00:24:03,632
Who am I?

216
00:24:04,673 --> 00:24:06,914
It doesn't matter, but you don't think about it.

217
00:24:07,315 --> 00:24:09,897
You just stay in that emptiness after the question.

218
00:24:10,258 --> 00:24:11,038
Like, what is this?

219
00:24:11,239 --> 00:24:11,859
And then you look.

220
00:24:14,442 --> 00:24:14,962
So now,

221
00:24:15,162 --> 00:24:22,349
As you focus down, you see, so you become, as you focus down, all the peripheral stuff begins to fade away.

222
00:24:23,230 --> 00:24:26,713
So you can become centered on the breath, and you don't hear anything.

223
00:24:26,854 --> 00:24:32,619
And then suddenly somebody coughs, and you can be shocked out of your meditation.

224
00:24:33,381 --> 00:24:39,027
Now, you might want to kill the person, but that's a good sign to you that you were fairly concentrated.

225
00:24:39,682 --> 00:24:45,288
There'll even come a point where you're so concentrated, somebody coughs, fires a gun, and you won't hear it.

226
00:24:46,769 --> 00:24:51,055
Because you've sort of brought yourself down into this singularity.

227
00:24:56,901 --> 00:24:59,384
Now, that's an effort.

228
00:24:59,784 --> 00:25:03,208
Now, that's all the effort you need to become...

229
00:25:04,015 --> 00:25:04,855
to become awakened.

230
00:25:05,256 --> 00:25:05,737
Just that.

231
00:25:05,997 --> 00:25:07,337
Just that of looking.

232
00:25:07,637 --> 00:25:10,842
Just like in the body, all the effort you need is just to keep the spine erect.

233
00:25:15,705 --> 00:25:19,630
You can get away with just breakfast.

234
00:25:19,650 --> 00:25:30,861
If you just have breakfast and meditate all day, within seven years, see, so it's the effort needed is a very gentle effort.

235
00:25:31,060 --> 00:25:33,042
So if there's any force comes in, if you

236
00:25:33,309 --> 00:25:36,053
If you feel that forcing, something's getting in there.

237
00:25:37,433 --> 00:25:38,855
You're trying to see.

238
00:25:40,396 --> 00:25:44,141
As soon as the trying to see comes in, there's the eye.

239
00:25:44,361 --> 00:25:45,762
It's looking for something.

240
00:25:48,025 --> 00:25:53,490
As soon as you know that, as soon as you get the tightness, you stay with the body, you can feel the tightness coming.

241
00:25:53,730 --> 00:25:54,872
So then you know, stop.

242
00:25:56,953 --> 00:25:59,717
Wanting to see something.

243
00:25:59,737 --> 00:26:02,118
That's not like you're looking for something.

244
00:26:02,520 --> 00:26:04,083
What we should be doing is just looking at.

245
00:26:05,924 --> 00:26:06,644
And have faith.

246
00:26:06,885 --> 00:26:10,689
You see, have faith that if you look at something, there will be a seeing.

247
00:26:12,070 --> 00:26:12,711
This is the Buddha.

248
00:26:12,731 --> 00:26:14,634
He says, first of all, just look at something.

249
00:26:14,973 --> 00:26:19,378
And the insight arises naturally.

250
00:26:19,398 --> 00:26:26,506
So, for instance, if your car breaks down and you open the bonnet, first you look, don't you?

251
00:26:26,526 --> 00:26:31,431
If you go to the bonnet with preconceived ideas as to what's happened, then you can be looking for a long time.

252
00:26:31,833 --> 00:26:34,556
But a trained mechanic, they know what they're looking for.

253
00:26:34,615 --> 00:26:39,461
They open the bonnet and they see.

254
00:26:39,481 --> 00:26:40,884
Same with the doctor.

255
00:26:40,903 --> 00:26:45,009
So it's a case of training ourselves to see these three characteristics.

256
00:26:46,269 --> 00:26:51,175
Now with something neutral like the breath, it's always the sense of transience.

257
00:26:51,195 --> 00:26:53,939
Always the sense of something arising and passing away.

258
00:26:54,880 --> 00:26:59,005
It can also be the sense of that distance, not me, not mine, that you can get.

259
00:27:00,115 --> 00:27:02,057
But remember that that's only a first position.

260
00:27:02,597 --> 00:27:08,924
Once you've created that objective stance, you go towards the object, investigate it.

261
00:27:11,888 --> 00:27:20,759
So that concentration is better developed when you draw up the interest of wanting to know.

262
00:27:21,740 --> 00:27:25,125
And you'll see there's a natural focusing in on the object.

263
00:27:26,787 --> 00:27:28,788
And just that effort of wanting to know

264
00:27:29,613 --> 00:27:30,114
That's enough.

265
00:27:30,795 --> 00:27:36,942
You don't have to go beyond that.

266
00:27:36,962 --> 00:27:41,869
Now, as you do that, this is supported by the calmness in the body.

267
00:27:45,114 --> 00:27:54,826
So that calmness in the body is balancing the joy that's coming from the interest.

268
00:27:55,567 --> 00:28:03,455
So sometimes you might, if the calmness goes a bit too far, then that's when you begin to get feelings of heaviness, sloth, torpor.

269
00:28:03,556 --> 00:28:04,317
There's too much of it.

270
00:28:05,439 --> 00:28:11,164
So when you feel that, you just lift the spine, correct your view, and just raise the interest.

271
00:28:11,986 --> 00:28:15,289
So the interest will raise the energy of wanting to know.

272
00:28:15,329 --> 00:28:23,700
If you start looking for something, so the interest overreaches itself, then you find yourself getting restless.

273
00:28:27,410 --> 00:28:30,433
So all these are little pointers to what's happening within us.

274
00:28:30,974 --> 00:28:44,271
So, you know, it's that sense of general awareness and then being aware of anything that's happening and then slowly just moving towards the object.

275
00:28:44,291 --> 00:28:48,837
Now, we've been primed and this is where the faith comes in, you see.

276
00:28:50,780 --> 00:28:56,808
What we've understood from the Buddha's teaching is that the delusion lies within the looking

277
00:28:58,257 --> 00:28:59,738
It doesn't lie within thought.

278
00:29:00,598 --> 00:29:03,021
The thought is only an expression of our delusion.

279
00:29:03,761 --> 00:29:05,723
It doesn't lie within the emotional life.

280
00:29:06,545 --> 00:29:09,048
That's only an expression of our delusion.

281
00:29:09,067 --> 00:29:12,770
The delusion lies deep within that which is looking.

282
00:29:13,291 --> 00:29:16,996
It can't see properly.

283
00:29:17,016 --> 00:29:18,856
There's a kink in the way it sees things.

284
00:29:21,380 --> 00:29:26,424
And what the Buddha points out is that this manifests in these three characteristics.

285
00:29:27,535 --> 00:29:36,365
So where there is real radical impermanence we have a sense of continuous time.

286
00:29:37,987 --> 00:29:43,233
But actually there's no such thing as time in any continuous sense.

287
00:29:43,253 --> 00:29:53,005
Time is just the way the mind relates events or experiences a sequence of moments.

288
00:29:54,307 --> 00:29:56,209
How long is a moment in time?

289
00:29:59,075 --> 00:30:00,856
Is it as long as the word time?

290
00:30:04,500 --> 00:30:05,603
It's a bit longer than time.

291
00:30:08,105 --> 00:30:14,794
How long do you experience an actual piece of time for?

292
00:30:20,921 --> 00:30:22,202
Interesting, isn't it?

293
00:30:22,222 --> 00:30:26,227
But at some point we lose the present.

294
00:30:26,327 --> 00:30:27,528
It suddenly becomes the past.

295
00:30:30,192 --> 00:30:36,220
But this present is long enough for us to believe that it's the same person moving through time.

296
00:30:36,881 --> 00:30:41,787
We've got this idea that there's time like a tunnel or something like that, and we're moving through it.

297
00:30:43,769 --> 00:30:51,980
So the past somehow exists in a way, and the future exists because we're going towards it.

298
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:55,344
But actually, nothing in any essence exists.

299
00:30:57,826 --> 00:31:00,029
When you get down to the actual...

300
00:31:00,397 --> 00:31:29,105
moment as it arises and passes away it's just a sudden coagulation of energy and it dissipates it's gone that's why when you keep watching the breath eventually you'll get down to a point where there's no breath all there is is a sequence of arising and falling away of sensations which is frightening

301
00:31:30,250 --> 00:31:32,834
Because before, you thought you existed.

302
00:31:33,855 --> 00:31:40,163
And this existence was based on your experience of your body, and of your emotions and thoughts.

303
00:31:44,609 --> 00:31:47,232
So it's beginning to perceive that.

304
00:31:47,554 --> 00:31:57,287
Now, the process is undoing, undermining all our concepts about who we are and what we are.

305
00:31:58,616 --> 00:31:59,939
We believe we're human beings.

306
00:32:00,778 --> 00:32:01,721
This is a big mistake.

307
00:32:08,488 --> 00:32:12,593
If the word being means anything beyond the present moment, it's a big mistake.

308
00:32:13,012 --> 00:32:20,041
Because at some point, the body of the human being will be as lifeless as a useless log, it says in the scripture.

309
00:32:20,501 --> 00:32:23,045
It'll just lie there, totally lifeless.

310
00:32:23,065 --> 00:32:24,826
Somebody will pick it up and chuck it in a hole.

311
00:32:27,642 --> 00:32:34,230
So, whatever we mean when I say, I am a human being, and you go into that as an investigation.

312
00:32:37,555 --> 00:32:41,580
Not much there, is there?

313
00:32:41,601 --> 00:32:49,050
Investigating that is to begin to realize that this self that we've constructed is a delusion.

314
00:32:50,071 --> 00:32:53,076
It doesn't exist.

315
00:32:55,807 --> 00:33:08,617
So by observing the quality of transience and by observing that quality of not me, not mine, we're undoing these essential misunderstandings we have.

316
00:33:09,838 --> 00:33:21,368
Now, if it were to lead us just to an annihilation, just to the fact that there was nothing there anyway, and that's the end of that, and when you die you disappear, then that would be depressing.

317
00:33:23,450 --> 00:33:25,392
But what the Buddha's saying is,

318
00:33:25,861 --> 00:33:54,923
that as you begin to perceive what you are not what you truly are becomes more and more obvious to you so the process is one of negation it's one of not me, not mine now to do that these spiritual faculties have to be clearly honed they've got to be nicely developed and you've got to be able to hold that steady gaze

319
00:33:55,190 --> 00:33:56,411
within the calmness.

320
00:33:59,374 --> 00:34:03,077
Keep the interest going and keep looking at these three qualities.

321
00:34:05,921 --> 00:34:22,699
Now even when the negative stuff comes up, even when the body now begins to shake with restlessness or it begins to feel heavy with tiredness or sloth and torpor, even then you can maintain that same quality of watchfulness.

322
00:34:23,050 --> 00:34:30,900
Even then there can be that quality of, as it were, calmness behind what's happening on the surface of the body and the mind.

323
00:34:32,121 --> 00:34:34,965
Even then you can maintain an interest.

324
00:34:34,985 --> 00:34:46,902
Even in dullness where all it is is just porridge in your head, you can wander about that and be completely awake as if you'd woken up brightly in the morning.

325
00:34:46,922 --> 00:34:49,686
Because it's within that awareness to be awake like that.

326
00:34:50,407 --> 00:34:52,769
It's only by way of association and habit

327
00:34:53,239 --> 00:34:59,126
That it keeps falling into that state of drowsiness and sloth and torpor.

328
00:35:01,710 --> 00:35:02,431
By way of habit.

329
00:35:02,610 --> 00:35:09,137
By way of, in the past, seeking refuge there.

330
00:35:09,157 --> 00:35:10,519
Seeking refuge in the bed.

331
00:35:14,204 --> 00:35:15,525
The final haven.

332
00:35:15,545 --> 00:35:17,407
When everything goes wrong, go to bed.

333
00:35:20,847 --> 00:35:24,710
Just when everything goes bad, you get this little neon sign come up.

334
00:35:24,731 --> 00:35:25,552
Head for the bed.

335
00:35:26,693 --> 00:35:27,112
That's it.

336
00:35:27,313 --> 00:35:31,318
You dive in and you wake up and you feel better, sort of, usually.

337
00:35:33,840 --> 00:35:36,623
And all you've done is use sleep to suppress, to push it down.

338
00:35:36,902 --> 00:35:41,867
Whatever it was that made you head for the bed.

339
00:35:42,289 --> 00:35:44,010
Now you begin to see all these things.

340
00:35:44,030 --> 00:35:50,297
You begin to see how we are moving away from what is unpleasant, moving towards what is pleasant.

341
00:35:51,086 --> 00:35:56,313
And that's that psychological vicious circle that we get caught up in.

342
00:35:56,333 --> 00:36:04,164
So again, having established this watchfulness, having got these seven faculties developed, you see, we begin to see that.

343
00:36:05,425 --> 00:36:10,152
Just the seeing and the understanding is the moment of liberation.

344
00:36:11,213 --> 00:36:15,780
It's the moment of liberation in the sense like a moment, ah, now I understand.

345
00:36:16,360 --> 00:36:18,664
But then, of course, there comes the trainings.

346
00:36:20,550 --> 00:36:26,217
If it were just that, well, I should think in a very short while we'd be all fully awakened.

347
00:36:26,237 --> 00:36:34,567
If it were just a matter of seeing these things, I should think we'd be very quickly out of this state.

348
00:36:35,887 --> 00:36:42,375
But the problem is that the conditioning is so heavy and so deep that you have to keep working against it all the time.

349
00:36:45,119 --> 00:36:47,862
So here on this retreat, you're moving forward a bit.

350
00:36:48,262 --> 00:36:49,123
Then you leave.

351
00:36:49,407 --> 00:36:51,289
And you say, to hell with it, and you go back a bit.

352
00:36:53,273 --> 00:36:55,476
This visual life is like up and down, up and down.

353
00:36:56,639 --> 00:36:59,885
That's why it takes so long to look back and think, oh, something might be happening.

354
00:37:01,628 --> 00:37:04,293
So that effort has to be kept up even in daily life.

355
00:37:05,353 --> 00:37:10,844
Remember, this is not whipping yourself or kicking yourself or forcing yourself.

356
00:37:12,166 --> 00:37:15,110
It's a gentle self-cajoling, encouraging yourself.

357
00:37:20,980 --> 00:37:32,076
So, just to revise these seven factors that we've tried to distinguish in our meditation, in which you, in every sitting, that's how you should begin.

358
00:37:32,336 --> 00:37:34,960
You should begin by trying to establish that state.

359
00:37:35,922 --> 00:37:38,346
If you lose it, go back, start again.

360
00:37:39,567 --> 00:37:41,771
Bring yourself back to the breath, etc., etc.

361
00:37:44,934 --> 00:37:49,501
When I say lose it, I mean when there's too much thought around.

362
00:37:50,173 --> 00:38:18,239
but remember that sometimes the mind is just like that it goes mad and you just have to have patience and you just keep bringing it back and bringing it back and remember that you can have these seven factors even though there's a negative mental state there you can still see the quality of transience as we've mentioned the depression you can still see how you relate to that depression which is understanding how we create suffering

363
00:38:18,862 --> 00:38:22,327
you can still see that there is depression, not me, not mine.

364
00:38:23,329 --> 00:38:34,786
So these factors of enlightenment, as it were, are sitting behind, as it were, or beneath the presenting quality that's arising in the mind.

365
00:38:41,295 --> 00:38:45,661
So the essential quality is this sati, this awareness, the knowings.

366
00:38:48,157 --> 00:38:53,322
And what empowers us, what empowers the meditation is that sense of interest, the wanting to know.

367
00:38:53,362 --> 00:38:57,628
And it's wanting to know something quite specific.

368
00:38:57,748 --> 00:38:59,871
It's wanting to know these three characteristics.

369
00:38:59,891 --> 00:39:05,018
It's wanting to experience them, to see them very clearly.

370
00:39:05,498 --> 00:39:08,061
And to support that, the body has to support it.

371
00:39:08,702 --> 00:39:10,143
So there has to be that stillness.

372
00:39:11,525 --> 00:39:16,931
So even though you might feel depressed in the chest, the body can still be quite energized and relaxed.

373
00:39:17,856 --> 00:39:24,085
Even though you feel restless, very restless, you can still relax the body around that restlessness.

374
00:39:28,472 --> 00:39:37,083
So that quality of what's known as pities, often it's translated as bliss I think, which is way over the top.

375
00:39:37,585 --> 00:39:44,775
It's just that sense of joy in the body and the calmness of the body balancing each other.

376
00:39:45,784 --> 00:39:47,748
And what's driving that is that interest.

377
00:39:48,369 --> 00:39:50,692
And then you're investigating the Dharma.

378
00:39:50,811 --> 00:39:52,795
You're investigating these three characteristics.

379
00:39:53,576 --> 00:40:00,405
And to investigate that you have to come at it as somebody who doesn't know.

380
00:40:00,465 --> 00:40:02,389
You don't know.

381
00:40:02,889 --> 00:40:04,773
You've heard this from the Buddha but you don't know.

382
00:40:07,056 --> 00:40:08,217
So you've got to keep looking.

383
00:40:08,297 --> 00:40:10,840
So you've come from a point of no position.

384
00:40:12,744 --> 00:40:14,085
You've not taken a position.

385
00:40:14,346 --> 00:40:15,487
You're not saying to yourself

386
00:40:15,686 --> 00:40:17,791
The Buddha said everything's transient, so it must be right.

387
00:40:19,132 --> 00:40:22,659
If the Buddha says everything's transient, I'm not so sure about that.

388
00:40:22,719 --> 00:40:23,960
Let's have a look.

389
00:40:23,981 --> 00:40:25,844
So it's a case of that investigation.

390
00:40:27,867 --> 00:40:28,668
That equanimity.

391
00:40:29,931 --> 00:40:33,677
And you have to be careful with the sense of achievement.

392
00:40:33,777 --> 00:40:37,003
It's a sort of difficult word for us in English because

393
00:40:37,556 --> 00:41:07,445
achievement is always something in the future you're doing something now to achieve something in the next moment in the next year by the end of your life when I'm retired I will achievement is always ahead of time but if you define your achievement if you want to use that word as being aware in this present moment then that's the achievement so to be aware is to be there there's nowhere else to go

394
00:41:08,809 --> 00:41:18,920
So if you think about achievement in your meditation, don't think about some sort of insight, or where you'll be in ten years' time or something, or what you're going to do, you know, like planning to live in the now.

395
00:41:19,280 --> 00:41:19,922
That's a lovely one.

396
00:41:21,963 --> 00:41:26,548
Actually, just bring yourself, just say to yourself, am I aware?

397
00:41:26,588 --> 00:41:29,552
Yes, well, that's it, that's the achievement, I'm aware.

398
00:41:29,572 --> 00:41:29,891
That's it.

399
00:41:30,072 --> 00:41:31,034
Once you're aware, you're there.

400
00:41:31,313 --> 00:41:32,454
So you keep saying that to yourself.

401
00:41:33,356 --> 00:41:34,277
It's a secret mantra.

402
00:41:36,585 --> 00:41:37,786
I'm aware, I must be there.

403
00:41:38,728 --> 00:41:39,108
I've done it.

404
00:41:40,851 --> 00:41:46,177
And so, get rid of the idea of something achieving in the future time, you see.

405
00:41:46,197 --> 00:41:47,219
So, awareness.

406
00:41:48,360 --> 00:41:51,503
And we can actually make things very simple for ourselves.

407
00:41:52,204 --> 00:42:00,155
Sometimes, especially for those of you who are more established in your meditation, you can see these faculties, you can do things to balance them.

408
00:42:00,275 --> 00:42:02,036
So that's the skills of meditation.

409
00:42:03,012 --> 00:42:11,260
But for those of you who are new, and all this sounds very complicated, what, seven of these, ten of those, and five.

410
00:42:11,280 --> 00:42:19,708
You can actually put all that aside because the one factor which draws everything into balance is that awareness.

411
00:42:19,728 --> 00:42:22,811
And that's the sort of key discovery of the Buddha.

412
00:42:23,632 --> 00:42:31,820
Once you place your awareness on something with right intention, to observe the characteristics or to be stilled,

413
00:42:32,188 --> 00:42:36,117
then all these faculties just come up to support that awareness.

414
00:42:41,507 --> 00:42:47,539
Now that awareness, you might say, is our intuitive intelligence, but it's in its passive mode.

415
00:42:48,300 --> 00:42:51,547
In a passive mode, it's receiving, to be aware of.

416
00:42:52,304 --> 00:42:56,528
And as that information comes in, there's a sudden seeing.

417
00:42:57,230 --> 00:43:05,059
So that awareness has an active mode of an intuitive understanding which is known as paññā.

418
00:43:05,079 --> 00:43:09,483
And you will notice that our trust is called satipaññā.

419
00:43:09,503 --> 00:43:12,126
Satipaññā is the Buddha mind.

420
00:43:12,146 --> 00:43:19,454
It's that which is to be liberated, to be awakened, to be enlightened.

421
00:43:19,474 --> 00:43:21,838
So, having said all that,

422
00:43:22,190 --> 00:43:26,273
Having gone on like this for too long.

423
00:43:26,293 --> 00:43:34,483
There is a very simple approach which is just to keep placing the awareness on the object.

424
00:43:35,123 --> 00:43:50,880
Just that activity of wanting to feel, experience exactly what's going on now, whether it's the subtle feelings of the breath or the feelings that are associated with a heavy state or a beautiful state, that's enough.

425
00:43:51,755 --> 00:44:21,677
just doing that you see and the insights will arise remember these insights are not cataclysmic they're just little incremental points which over a period of time for most people build up to a change in the way we see things it's a change within consciousness and when that change begins to take place it has a systemic effect it affects the way it affects your attitude to things

426
00:44:22,163 --> 00:44:25,726
So if you see transience, then of course you don't hold on so much.

427
00:44:26,608 --> 00:44:31,632
So when you're watching the TV and somebody phones you, you can turn it off right in the middle of a soap.

428
00:44:33,034 --> 00:44:37,639
It doesn't matter, right just as he's about to score the goal, you can turn it off and go and answer the phone.

429
00:44:39,722 --> 00:44:39,802
See?

430
00:44:39,822 --> 00:44:41,284
Before you couldn't do that.

431
00:44:41,304 --> 00:44:42,065
Now you've understood.

432
00:44:42,144 --> 00:44:51,715
So it's a case of this change becoming a change of attitude and that immediately expresses itself in the way we speak

433
00:44:53,246 --> 00:44:56,711
In what we do and how we do things.

434
00:44:57,514 --> 00:44:58,614
And in our livelihood.

435
00:44:58,916 --> 00:45:01,559
People change their livelihood if they meditate sometimes.

436
00:45:02,240 --> 00:45:07,750
Because they find themselves in a livelihood which they find doesn't fit with the Dharma.

437
00:45:07,929 --> 00:45:09,592
So they make this effort to move over.

438
00:45:10,494 --> 00:45:10,833
Change.

439
00:45:10,974 --> 00:45:12,836
Even if it means a loss of wealth.

440
00:45:13,518 --> 00:45:17,505
A dislocation.

441
00:45:17,525 --> 00:45:17,684
See?

442
00:45:17,969 --> 00:45:27,157
Now, just as that happens that way, outwardly, from understanding into livelihood, remember, it's also coming back the other way.

443
00:45:27,737 --> 00:45:31,521
So your livelihood has a great effect on your attitude.

444
00:45:32,161 --> 00:45:34,704
It has a great effect on your general understanding.

445
00:45:35,686 --> 00:45:38,989
So as you know, if you're trained as a policeman, you're always suspicious.

446
00:45:40,210 --> 00:45:40,751
You have to be.

447
00:45:41,931 --> 00:45:43,132
You're trained to be suspicious.

448
00:45:44,173 --> 00:45:45,494
Anybody you see, you think, I am.

449
00:45:50,032 --> 00:45:53,481
If you're a soldier, you're trained to kill.

450
00:45:56,550 --> 00:45:59,619
So your profession

451
00:45:59,802 --> 00:46:02,144
Those, of course, are heavy examples.

452
00:46:02,686 --> 00:46:12,119
If you're a nurse or a doctor or in a more helping profession, then you're developing that compassion, usually.

453
00:46:12,139 --> 00:46:18,027
So, remember that the whole of the teaching is one composite.

454
00:46:18,086 --> 00:46:18,807
It's a mandala.

455
00:46:19,248 --> 00:46:23,213
As soon as you affect one part, the whole mandala changes.

456
00:46:23,233 --> 00:46:25,496
Something happens.

457
00:46:25,516 --> 00:46:27,480
So, I hope that...

458
00:46:29,367 --> 00:46:45,264
That little exercise, explanation, does clarify for you these factors of enlightenment and how to establish them and to use them in order to gain slowly, just to gain little insights and change our view of things.

459
00:46:45,284 --> 00:46:54,835
So I hope that's been a benefit and I can only hope that your liberation is sooner rather than later.

